Its advantage over writing is in the scope of its appeal. Visual media is easier to digest and disperse across linguistic and generic barriers where written works may stagnate. You wouldn't need to be a furry, fluent in English (idiosyncracies included), or a fan of sci-fi to appreciate a visual depiction of anthropomorphic pilots dogfighting in deep space as two massive warships collide. Readers without interests in those genres, or readers who struggle with English literature, would need a lot more patience to appreciate the quality and appeal of what they're consuming, assuming they'll even enjoy at all. Both mediums require time and effort to perfect, but the product of the brush will always have broader appeal than its written counterpart. In any case, I had the same problem growing up, but with recent developments, I'm really enjoying myself when I draw these days.

Where this is concerned the thing about art is also that it's naturally divided in easy to consume chunks.
